<h3>Reconciliation Layer</h3>

<p>
The reconciliation layer is where imported state is evaluated against existing
records so the app can identify what should be created, updated, retained, or
flagged for review. It provides consistency controls that keep sync results
stable across repeated runs.
</p>

<p>
This section is currently placeholder content and will later describe the
specific reconciliation contracts, boundary rules, and how reconciliation output
is surfaced in the interface and logs.
</p>

<h3>Orchestration Layer</h3>

<p>
The orchestration layer coordinates the runtime sync process and manages how API
work is sequenced for each tenant. It governs execution order, dispatch timing,
and job-level coordination so sync runs remain predictable.
</p>

<p>
Detailed content will be added here later to document orchestration internals,
error handling strategy, retry behavior, and how orchestration events map to
observable job states.
</p>

<h3>Chunking and Cancellation</h3>

<p>
Chunking divides larger sync workloads into manageable units so the app can
track progress incrementally and control processing pressure. This structure
also supports clearer status reporting across long-running operations.
</p>

<p>
Cancellation behavior will be documented in detail in a later update, including
how stop requests are handled at runtime and what completion or partial state
should be expected after interruption.
</p>
